GRAPH EXPLORER FRONTEND ROADMAP (PHASED, HIGH ROI -> LOW ROI)
Audience: implementation agents. Style: step-by-step, minimal ambiguity.
Goal: make graph feel premium: clarity, trust (evidence), speed, workflow.

GLOBAL PRINCIPLES (apply everywhere)
- Canvas is sacred: details should be peekable/temporary unless pinned.
- One action = one obvious result. No “mystery state”.
- Evidence-first UI: edges carry trust. Nodes carry identity.
- Prefer progressive enhancement: ship scaffolds early, deepen later.
- Avoid global relayout on every merge; favor local updates.

DATA / UI TERMINOLOGY
- Selection: none | node | edge | multi
- Inspector: right-side sheet/drawer for selection details + actions
- Lens: curated multi-step /graph/query expansion
- Typed expand: per-node-type expansion button (edgeTypes + direction + limit + sort)
- BFS expand: /graph/subgraph “Expand all neighbors”

                                                                                                                     frontend merge logic would be:            
  on expansion response:                                                                                                                
    for each node in response.data.nodes:                                                                                               
      if node key NOT in canvas → add node
      if node key already in canvas → skip (already rendered)

    for each edge in response.data.edges:
      add edge (connects to existing or new nodes)

================================================================
PHASE 1 — GOD MODE FEEL (Highest ROI, simplest)
Focus: selection UX + space + immediate clarity

1.1 Replace fixed right panel with Sheet (Peek → Pin → Full)
- Default: “Peek” overlay (does not permanently shrink canvas)
- Pin: becomes persistent
- Full: expands to wide details mode
- Close: Esc + click background
DoD:
- Selecting node/edge opens sheet
- Pin/unpin persists across selections
- Sheet responsive: desktop right-sheet, mobile bottom-sheet

1.2 Hover highlighting (zero-click sensemaking)
- Hover node: highlight node + 1-hop neighbors + connecting edges; fade others
- Hover edge: highlight endpoints + the edge; fade others
DoD:
- Smooth fade (no jank)
- Works with filters + hidden nodes

1.3 Edge tooltip (micro evidence)
- On edge hover: show edgeType + direction + 2–3 key fields (schema-aware)
Examples:
- ASSOCIATED_WITH_DISEASE: overall_score, evidence_count, source
- TARGETS: action_type, num_sources, max_clinical_phase
DoD:
- Tooltip appears near cursor, does not clip offscreen

1.4 Selection polish
- Node click: select + center (optional toggle)
- Double click: Focus mode (see Phase 3) placeholder button ok
- Background click: clear selection
DoD:
- Selection state always consistent; never “stuck”

================================================================
PHASE 2 — TRUST LAYER (Edges become real objects)
Focus: edge inspector content + evidence scaffold

2.1 Edge Inspector: Summary section
- Header: EDGE_TYPE + direction + endpoint chips (clickable)
- Confidence badge: derived heuristic (score + evidence_count + curated/inferred)
- Key fields: schema-aware 3–6 fields
DoD:
- Clicking an edge shows meaningful info beyond type

2.2 Evidence Tab (scaffold now, deepen later)
- If includeEvidence=false: show “Load evidence” CTA
- If includeEvidence=true: render evidence list/table
- Always show external resources when available (e.g., DrugBank link)
DoD:
- Evidence area exists + supports pagination/“top N”

2.3 Node Inspector: “Why am I seeing this?”
- A short generated sentence from fields (“Supported by X sources / Y evidence”)
DoD:
- Present for major edge types (Gene–Disease, Drug–Gene, Drug–Disease)

================================================================
PHASE 3 — VISUAL GRAMMAR (13 types become instantly parseable)
Focus: shape/icon/size, legends, and focus tools

3.1 Node shapes + icons per entity type
Suggested mapping:
- Gene circle, Disease hexagon, Drug pill/round-rect, Variant diamond,
  Pathway parallelogram/round-rect, Phenotype triangle, Trait square,
  Study document badge, GOTerm octagon, SideEffect warning/inverted triangle,
  OntologyTerm tag, cCRE small round-rect “DNA” badge, Metabolite circle+dot
DoD:
- At least shape differs across core types (Gene/Disease/Drug/Variant)
- Legend reflects shapes + colors

3.2 Meaningful node sizing (toggle)
- Default: degree within visible graph
- Option: lens-specific “evidence sizing” (e.g., overall_score/evidence_count)
DoD:
- Size toggle works without relayout chaos

3.3 Focus Mode v1 (reduce getting lost)
- Action on node: “Isolate neighborhood (depth 1/2)”
- Action: “Restore full graph”
DoD:
- Users can declutter without losing state

================================================================
PHASE 4 — WORKFLOW FEATURES (Graphs for discovery, tables for decisions)
Focus: breadcrumbs, undo/redo, tables, compare

4.1 Breadcrumb trail (expansion history)
- Append entries: Seed → edgeType/direction → results (top K by sort)
- Click breadcrumb: re-center and/or restore that substate (lightweight ok)
DoD:
- Trail persists during session; clear on lens switch optional

4.2 Undo/Redo (expansions + hides + filters)
- Record actions: typed expand, BFS expand, hide/isolate, filter toggles, layout changes
DoD:
- Ctrl/Cmd+Z and Ctrl/Cmd+Shift+Z supported

4.3 Table view (neighbors as sortable list)
- For selected node: “Neighbors Table”
  Columns: neighbor label, type, edgeType, key score fields, source(s)
- For selected edge: “Evidence Table”
DoD:
- Sort + quick filter + copy/export CSV (export can be later)

4.4 Multi-select compare (lightweight)
- For multi nodes: shared neighbors + unique neighbors (top N)
DoD:
- Compare UI exists; can be basic

================================================================
PHASE 5 — PERFORMANCE + SCALE (Make it buttery)
Focus: progressive rendering, stable layouts, virtualization

5.1 Progressive render
- Render nodes first, edges in batches
- Show “loading edges…” indicator unobtrusive
DoD:
- Large merges feel responsive

5.2 Layout stabilization
- Avoid full relayout on merge
- Local layout around newly added nodes
- “Freeze layout” toggle
DoD:
- Expanding doesn’t explode the whole graph every time

5.3 Virtualize long lists
- Evidence tables, legends, edge type lists (accordion) virtualized
DoD:
- Inspector scroll stays smooth with large evidence

================================================================
PHASE 6 — ADVANCED EXPLORATION (Power-user tier)
Focus: overlays, command palette, pathfinding

6.1 Lens overlays (layers)
- Allow overlay 2nd lens on same seed(s)
- Color/line-style by lens
DoD:
- Overlay on/off without losing base graph

6.2 Command palette (Cmd/Ctrl+K)
Actions:
- Jump to entity by ID/name
- Switch lens
- Expand typed neighbors
- Toggle edge groups
- Run “isolate neighborhood”
DoD:
- Palette searches local nodes + can trigger actions

6.3 Shortest path / explain connection (optional)
- Between two selected nodes: compute path (backend or client if available)
- Display path with evidence highlights
DoD:
- Clear output; never blocks UI

================================================================
PHASE 7 — EXTRA POLISH (Lowest ROI, but delightful)
7.1 Micro-interactions
- Selection glow/pulse
- “New nodes fly-in” from expanded node
- Filter edges fade vs pop
7.2 Saved views
- Save current lens + filters + pinned nodes + layout
7.3 Shareable link state
- URL encodes seed + lens + filters + selected node/edge

